![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

The new PNG decoding implementation is significantly more fragile than the `image` crate it replaces. It currently panics on common color types like `Grayscale` and `GrayscaleAlpha`, and it does not handle 16-bit images correctly (which will result in corrupted textures or panics because the buffer size and pixel strides will differ from expectations).

Adding the `STRIP_16` transformation and handling grayscale types by expanding them to RGBA will make this much more robust.

```rust
        decoder.set_transformations(png::Transformations::EXPAND | png::Transformations::STRIP_16);
        let mut reader = decoder.read_info().expect("Failed to read PNG info");
        let mut buf = vec![0; reader.output_buffer_size().expect("Invalid PNG")];
        let info = reader.next_frame(&mut buf).expect("Failed to decode PNG");
        buf.truncate(info.buffer_size());

        let (width, height) = (info.width, info.height);
        let data: Vec<u8> = match info.color_type {
            png::ColorType::Rgba => buf,
            png::ColorType::Rgb => {
                let mut rgba = Vec::with_capacity(buf.len() / 3 * 4);
                for chunk in buf.chunks_exact(3) {
                    rgba.extend_from_slice(chunk);
                    rgba.push(255);
                }
                rgba
            }
            png::ColorType::Grayscale => {
                let mut rgba = Vec::with_capacity(buf.len() * 4);
                for &g in &buf {
                    rgba.extend_from_slice(&[g, g, g, 255]);
                }
                rgba
            }
            png::ColorType::GrayscaleAlpha => {
                let mut rgba = Vec::with_capacity(buf.len() / 2 * 4);
                for chunk in buf.chunks_exact(2) {
                    let g = chunk[0];
                    let a = chunk[1];
                    rgba.extend_from_slice(&[g, g, g, a]);
                }
                rgba
            }
            _ => panic!("Unsupported PNG color type: {:?}", info.color_type),
        };
```

![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

The Bun build path should respect the `CI` environment variable by running workspaces sequentially when it is set, mirroring the behavior of the `npm` build path (lines 63-65). This is important for stability and resource management in CI environments. Additionally, use double quotes for the filter patterns to ensure compatibility with Windows shells.

```javascript
  if (process.env.CI) {
    console.log('CI environment detected. Building workspaces sequentially...');
    execSync('bun run --filter "*" --filter "!@google/gemini-cli-core" build', {
      stdio: 'inherit',
      cwd: root,
    });
  } else {
    console.log('Building other workspaces in parallel...');
    execSync(
      'bun run --filter "*" --filter "!@google/gemini-cli-core" --parallel build',
      { stdio: 'inherit', cwd: root },
    );
  }
```

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

Use wrapping arithmetic (`wrapping_add`) to match C's unsigned overflow behavior. In C, `uint32_t` addition is defined to wrap, whereas in Rust, the `+` operator will panic in debug builds if an overflow occurs. This is important for maintaining identical behavior between the C and Rust implementations, especially in a low-level runtime library.

```suggestion
pub const fn point_add(a: TSPoint, b: TSPoint) -> TSPoint {
    if b.row > 0 {
        TSPoint { row: a.row.wrapping_add(b.row), column: b.column }
    } else {
        TSPoint { row: a.row, column: a.column.wrapping_add(b.column) }
    }
}
```

